2. Adapted taxonomy content  -  CC BY-SA 4.0 (share-alike)
--------------------------------------------------------

Portions of the pattern taxonomy in references/patterns.md,
references/weak-signals.md, and references/vocab-eras.md are adapted from:

    Wikipedia: "Signs of AI writing" (WikiProject AI Cleanup)
    https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Signs_of_AI_writing
    Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 (CC BY-SA 4.0).

    A condensed derivative was also consulted:
    ETB Libraries Ireland, "Signs of AI Writing"
    https://library.etbi.ie/sources2/aisigns (CC BY-SA).

Because CC BY-SA is a copyleft license, the adapted documentation content in the
three reference files is made available under CC BY-SA 4.0. If you redistribute
or modify those adapted portions, you must attribute the source and share your
changes under the same license. The MIT grant in Part 1 does not override this
requirement for the CC BY-SA-derived material.

CC BY-SA 4.0 full text: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/


3. Additional attribution
-------------------------

Structure and several before/after pairs are informed by:

    blader/humanizer by Siqi Chen (@blader)
    https://github.com/blader/humanizer
    MIT License. Announced 2026-01-18.
    (blader/humanizer is itself derived from the Wikipedia page above.)

Social/marketing-copy tells (patterns B14, B16) are informed, by paraphrase, by:

    Hunting the Muse, "How to spot when writing is AI: 6 elements of a robot's
    style"
    https://huntingthemuse.net/library/how-to-tell-if-writing-is-ai

No long passages from any source are reproduced. All examples are paraphrased or
original.


